iddlesex, England","London, England":"London, England","Clerkenwell, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"en":{"1198–1272":"1198–1272","1214–1303":"1214–1303","–1263":"–1263","–Female":"Deceased","1217–1299":"1217–1299","1163–1239":"1163–1239","1169–1245":"1169–1245","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1163":"1163","1272":"1272","1217":"1217","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","23 December 1263":"23 December 1263","1214":"1214","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1245":"1245","1189":"1189","1299":"1299","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","London, England":"London, England","Clerkenwell, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Loch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Benno, Kurt, Gottfried, Hartmut, Helmut.","German: topographic name from Middle High German <i>loch</i> ‘hollow, valley, hole’.","Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived by a loch or lake, or, according to Black, specifically from Portmore Loch in Eddleston."],"variants":[{"name":"Lochmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Bernhard, Gerhard, Lothar, Otto.  Scandinavian Erik.","German:","topographic name for someone who lived by a hole or a valley (see   Loch  )."]},{"name":"Locher","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Ernst, Eugen, Horst, Manfred, Maximilian, Uwe.","South German (<b>Löcher</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several places in Bavaria and Austria named Lochen or Lohen.","German and Swiss German: variant of   Loch   1."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bourne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from southern Middle English <i>bourne</i>, Old English <i>burna</i>, <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Bourn in Cambridgeshire or Bourne in Lincolnshire. In surnames the reference is often to an old stream called <i>burna</i>, surviving as the name of a farm. This word was replaced as the general word for a stream in southern dialects by Old English <i>brōc</i> (see   Brook  ) and came to be restricted in meaning to a stream flowing only intermittently, especially in winter."],"variants":[{"name":"Burn","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: of various origins. In the case of the film actor  Burt Lancaster  (  1913–1994 ) it is a short form of   Burton  , but it has also been used as a variant spelling of   Bert .  The pianist and composer  Burt Bacharach  (  b. 1928 ) was the son of a  Bert Bacharach , and his given name is presumably simply a variation of his father's."]},{"name":"Bourn","meanings":["English (southeastern): variant of   Bourne  ."]},{"name":"Born","meanings":["from an Old Norse byname meaning ‘bear’. It is also a short form of compound names such as   Arnbjörn   and   Torbjörn ."]},{"name":"Cockburn","meanings":["Scottish (Midlothian) and northern English: habitational name from a place in Berwickshire named Cockburn, from Old English <i>cocc</i> ‘cock, rooster’ (or the related byname <i>Cocca</i>) + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’ (see   Bourne  ). This surname is traditionally pronounced <i>Coburn</i>."]},{"name":"Bournes","meanings":["English: variant of   Bourne   with plural or post-medieval exrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Brook","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, originally a local name for someone who lived near a brook or stream (Old English <i>bróc</i>). It is borne by the American actress  Brooke Adams  (  b. 1949 ), but is probably more closely identified with her compatriot  Brooke Shields  (  b. 1965 )."]},{"name":"Burne","meanings":["English: variant of   Bourne  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":17,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":26,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":61,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Bourne de  Loch was born in 1198, in London, Middlesex, England, his father, William Bourne, was 35 and his mother, Johanna de Percy, was 29. He had at least 1 son with Isabel de Vere. He died in 1272, in his hometown, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1198–1272":"1198–1272","1214–1303":"1214–1303","–1263":"–1263","–Female":"Surnud","1217–1299":"1217–1299","1163–1239":"1163–1239","1169–1245":"1169–1245","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1163":"1163","1272":"1272","1217":"1217","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","23 December 1263":"23. detsember 1263","1214":"1214","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1245":"1245","1189":"1189","1299":"1299","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","London, England":"London, England","Clerkenwell, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"1198–1272":"1198–1272","1214–1303":"1214–1303","–1263":"–1263","–Female":"Kuollut","1217–1299":"1217–1299","1163–1239":"1163–1239","1169–1245":"1169–1245","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1163":"1163","1272":"1272","1217":"1217","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","23 December 1263":"23. joulukuuta 1263","1214":"1214","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1245":"1245","1189":"1189","1299":"1299","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","London, England":"London, England","Clerkenwell, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fr":{"1198–1272":"1198–1272","1214–1303":"1214–1303","–1263":"–1263","–Female":"Décédée","1217–1299":"1217–1299","1163–1239":"1163–1239","1169–1245":"1169–1245","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1163":"1163","1272":"1272","1217":"1217","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1215":"121